John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a string of achievements of academic excellence, and this was continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which were only reinforced by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other community ventures.
With more than 30,000 scholars across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their scholars and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career and their position as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a custom school curriculum, we see world languages continuing as a popular and desirable subject choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you talk to someone in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
It's a powerful reminder that we can't just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a higher grade A.
The data, collected from SCIS's 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students obtained a higher grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 of those who studied French, and 63 of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young adults will no doubt need in the future.
Languages now, as subjects, have the same prestige as the STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in independent schools' curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission on Professions and Skills in 2014 found that of the reasons employees are struggling to fill jobs, 17 percent are attributed to a shortage of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more likely jobs requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, in the future they will have a real advantage with such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically put a multilingual person above the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15 percent.
That's why it's so important to teach children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, every school will differ in the languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages will teach what are considered essential for the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills needed to achieve success, regardless of what the future holds.
It cannot be denied at this stage, in a global business environment, that languages are still extremely important for the country's future, and therefore they must be reflected in education.
Truly, modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's young people.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
