Harvard students take a course on getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year allows all its undergraduates to get more sleep in an effort to counter the growing macho culture of studying through caffeine-driven "all-night sessions."
An academic has found that students at the world's top university are often uninformed when it comes to the basics of how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical Faculty and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why are they only telling me this now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep is - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was presented for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how they improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical Faculty and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The hour-long course involves some interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a dormitory, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of a sleep schedule routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know this won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," Prof Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in "studying all night" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students has meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Making sure you get enough good-quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to avoid stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said - even avoiding putting on weight because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after taking one of its classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to strive for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete with each other.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and being aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
