National Trust listens to bats' secret life
New research is being conducted on an estate in the Scottish Highlands that aims to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common and soprano dwarf bat as well as the brown long-eared and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed on important locations on the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also do mobile surveys using hand-held indicators.
Expert clan analysis of all surveys will check the regularity of the bat calls and determine which species do.
A habitat map and report will then be compiled to create a detailed landscape-scale image of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as pastureland creation and how to best manage woodlands for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping space and loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as well as fly paper and some chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
The bats aren't really blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting activities, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-orientation technique to point out bugs and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, is very serious about bats.
It has ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys and sleeping spot inspections and sometimes carry out rescues.
The organisation even established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Estate manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal site for them.
"Here at Threave we have a wonderful area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of veteran trees and all the good habitat.
But there is so much about bats that is still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us better understand what they need to thrive."
He emphasizes the need to search for bats before maintenance in properties is done because it is possible that unwitting destruction of a single maternity site could mean up to 400 females and young ones dead and an entire local population could be wiped out.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb or prevent them or destroy their sleeping places.
Elizabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to jump in to help.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations fare."
